    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-12-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-12-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="1473"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1473">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.00/2207.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 90.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>. <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-12-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 21, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    the Department’s instruction No. 65 of the 18th ultimo (File 817.00/2130)
                    together with its enclosure of a copy of the Libro Rosado of Salvador for the
                    month of September, 1912, which treats at length of the recent revolution in
                    Nicaragua.</p>
                <p>On page 2 of the Libro Rosado is printed a telegram, dated Managua, August 5,
                    1912, in which the Salvadorian Minister, Señor J. Antonio López G., reports to
                    his Government a conversation with me and alleges that he obtained my “formal
                    promise” not to disembark another man besides those who were then guarding the
                    Legation.</p>
                <p>Of course I made no such promise, formal or otherwise, and I would have
                    considered it presumption on his part to have requested any.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">George T. Weitzel.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
